# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nonlinear-dynamics-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In the mathematical field of dynamical systems, an **attractor** is a set of states toward which a system tends to evolve, for a wide variety of starting conditions of the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] System values that get close enough to the attractor values remain close even if slightly disturbed.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In finite-dimensional systems, the evolving variable may be represented algebraically as an *n*-dimensional vector.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The attractor is a region in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In physical systems, the *n* dimensions may be, for example, two or three positional coordinates for each of one or more physical entities; in economic systems, they may be separate variables such as the inflation rate and the unemployment rate.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If the evolving variable is two- or three-dimensional, the attractor of the dynamic process can be represented geometrically in two or three dimensions, (as for example in the three-dimensional case depicted to the right).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] An attractor can be a point, a finite set of points, a curve, a manifold, or even a complicated set with a fractal structure known as a *strange attractor* (see strange attractor below).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If the variable is a scalar, the attractor is a subset of the real number line.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Describing the attractors of chaotic dynamical systems has been one of the achievements of chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A trajectory of the dynamical system in the attractor does not have to satisfy any special constraints except for remaining on the attractor, forward in time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The trajectory may be periodic or chaotic.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If a set of points is periodic or chaotic, but the flow in the neighborhood is away from the set, the set is not an attractor, but instead is called a *repeller* (or *repellor*).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A dynamical system is generally described by one or more differential or difference equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The equations of a given dynamical system specify its behavior over any given short period of time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] To determine the system's behavior for a longer period, it is often necessary to integrate the equations, either through analytical means or through iteration, often with the aid of computers.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Dynamical systems in the physical world tend to arise from dissipative systems: if it were not for some driving force, the motion would cease.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] (Dissipation may come from internal friction, thermodynamic losses, or loss of material, among many causes.) The dissipation and the driving force tend to balance, killing off initial transients and settle the system into its typical behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The subset of the phase space of the dynamical system corresponding to the typical behavior is the attractor, also known as the attracting section or attractee.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Invariant sets and limit sets are similar to the attractor concept.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] An *invariant set* is a set that evolves to itself under the dynamics.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A *limit set* is a set of points such that there exists some initial state that ends up arbitrarily close to the limit set (i.e. to each point of the set) as time goes to infinity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Attractors are limit sets, but not all limit sets are attractors: It is possible to have some points of a system converge to a limit set, but different points when perturbed slightly off the limit set may get knocked off and never return to the vicinity of the limit set.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For example, the damped pendulum has two invariant points: the point *x*0 of minimum height and the point *x*1 of maximum height.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The point x0 is also a limit set, as trajectories converge to it; the point *x*1 is not a limit set.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Because of the dissipation due to air resistance, the point x0 is also an attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If there was no dissipation, *x*0 would not be an attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Aristotle believed that objects moved only as long as they were pushed, which is an early formulation of a dissipative attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Some attractors are known to be chaotic (see strange attractor), in which case the evolution of any two distinct points of the attractor result in exponentially diverging trajectories, which complicates prediction when even the smallest noise is present in the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Let t represent time and let $f(t,\cdot )$ be a function which specifies the dynamics of the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] That is, if a is a point in an n -dimensional phase space, representing the initial state of the system, then $f(0,a)=a$ and, for a positive value of t , $f(t,a)$ is the result of the evolution of this state after t units of time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Since the basin of attraction contains an open set containing A , every point that is sufficiently close to A is attracted to A .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The definition of an attractor uses a metric on the phase space, but the resulting notion usually depends only on the topology of the phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In the case of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the Euclidean norm is typically used.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Many other definitions of attractor occur in the literature.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For example, some authors require that an attractor have positive measure (preventing a point from being an attractor), others relax the requirement that $B(A)$ be a neighborhood.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Attractors are portions or subsets of the phase space of a dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Until the 1960s, attractors were thought of as being simple geometric subsets of the phase space, like points, lines, surfaces, and simple regions of three-dimensional space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] More complex attractors that cannot be categorized as simple geometric subsets, such as topologically wild sets, were known of at the time but were thought to be fragile anomalies.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Stephen Smale was able to show that his horseshoe map was robust and that its attractor had the structure of a Cantor set.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Two simple attractors are a fixed point and the limit cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Attractors can take on many other geometric shapes (phase space subsets).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] But when these sets (or the motions within them) cannot be easily described as simple combinations (e.g. intersection and union) of fundamental geometric objects (e.g. lines, surfaces, spheres, toroids, manifolds), then the attractor is called a *strange attractor*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A fixed point of a function or transformation is a point that is mapped to itself by the function or transformation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If we regard the evolution of a dynamical system as a series of transformations, then there may or may not be a point which remains fixed under each transformation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] But the fixed point(s) of a dynamic system is not necessarily an attractor of the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For example, if the bowl containing a rolling marble was inverted and the marble was balanced on top of the bowl, the center bottom (now top) of the bowl is a fixed state, but not an attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] This is equivalent to the difference between stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl (a hill), that point at the top of the bowl (hill) is a fixed point (equilibrium), but not an attractor (unstable equilibrium).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl, even if the bowl seems perfectly hemispherical, and the marble's spherical shape, are both much more complex surfaces when examined under a microscope, and their shapes change or deform during contact.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Any physical surface can be seen to have a rough terrain of multiple peaks, valleys, saddle points, ridges, ravines, and plains.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] There are many points in this surface terrain (and the dynamic system of a similarly rough marble rolling around on this microscopic terrain) that are considered stationary or fixed points, some of which are categorized as attractors.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] In a discrete-time system, an attractor can take the form of a finite number of points that are visited in sequence.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Each of these points is called a periodic point.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] This is illustrated by the logistic map, which depending on its specific parameter value can have an attractor consisting of 1 point, 2 points, 2*n* points, 3 points, 3×2*n* points, 4 points, 5 points, or any given positive integer number of points.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A limit cycle is a periodic orbit of a continuous dynamical system that is isolated.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Examples include the swings of a pendulum clock, and the heartbeat while resting.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For a physical pendulum under friction, the resting state will be a fixed-point attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The difference with the clock pendulum is that there, energy is injected by the escapement mechanism to maintain the cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] There may be more than one frequency in the periodic trajectory of the system through the state of a limit cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For example, in physics, one frequency may dictate the rate at which a planet orbits a star while a second frequency describes the oscillations in the distance between the two bodies.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If two of these frequencies form an irrational fraction (i.e. they are incommensurate), the trajectory is no longer closed, and the limit cycle becomes a limit torus.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] This kind of attractor is called an *N**t* -torus if there are Nt incommensurate frequencies.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A time series corresponding to this attractor is a quasiperiodic series: A discretely sampled sum of Nt periodic functions (not necessarily sine waves) with incommensurate frequencies.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Such a time series does not have a strict periodicity, but its power spectrum still consists only of sharp lines.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] An attractor is called *strange* if it has a fractal structure; that is, if it has non-integer Hausdorff dimension.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] This is often the case when the dynamics on it are chaotic, but strange nonchaotic attractors also exist.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Thus a dynamic system with a chaotic attractor is locally unstable yet globally stable: once some sequences have entered the attractor, nearby points diverge from one another but never depart from the attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The term *strange attractor* was coined by David Ruelle and Floris Takens to describe the attractor resulting from a series of bifurcations of a system describing fluid flow.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Strange attractors are often differentiable in a few directions, but some are like a Cantor dust, and therefore not differentiable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Strange attractors may also be found in the presence of noise, where they may be shown to support invariant random probability measures of Sinai–Ruelle–Bowen type.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Examples of strange attractors include the double-scroll attractor, Hénon attractor, Rössler attractor, and Lorenz attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The behavior of a dynamical system may be influenced by its parameters or the choice of initial conditions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The logistic map, defined as $x_{n+1}=rx_{n}(1-x_{n})$ , is a well-studied example of a system dependent on one parameter r .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Its attractors for various values of r are shown in the figure.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For small r the attractor is a single fixed point, which is shown on the bifurcation diagram as one line.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For other choices of r , more than one value of x may become attracting: at $r\approx 3$ the fixed point splits in two creating a period 2 cycle during a period-doubling bifurcation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] As r increases, chaos emerges through a period-doubling cascade, meaning the attractor consists of an infinte number of points.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] At $r\approx 3.83$ a period 3 orbit can be found.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] It follows from the Sharkovskii's theorem that orbits of any natural period are present in the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Thus one dynamic equation can have vastly different attractors depending on the choice of parameters.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] An attractor's basin of attraction is the region of the phase space, over which iterations are defined, such that any point (any initial condition) in that region will asymptotically be iterated into the attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For a stable linear system, every point in the phase space is in the basin of attraction.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] However, in nonlinear systems, some points may map directly or asymptotically to infinity, while other points may lie in a different basin of attraction and map asymptotically into a different attractor; other initial conditions may be in or map directly into a non-attracting point or cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] A univariate linear homogeneous difference equation $x_{t}=ax_{t-1}$ diverges to infinity if $|a|>1$ from all initial points except 0; there is no attractor and therefore no basin of attraction.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] But if $|a|<1$ all points on the number line map asymptotically (or directly in the case of 0) to 0; 0 is the attractor, and the entire number line is the basin of attraction.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] But if the largest eigenvalue is less than 1 in magnitude, all initial vectors will asymptotically converge to the zero vector, which is the attractor; the entire n -dimensional space of potential initial vectors is the basin of attraction.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Similar features apply to linear differential equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The scalar equation $dx/dt=ax$ causes all initial values of x except zero to diverge to infinity if $a>0$ but to converge to an attractor at the value 0 if $a<0$ , making the entire number line the basin of attraction for 0.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] And the matrix system $dX/dt=AX$ gives divergence from all initial points except the vector of zeroes if any eigenvalue of the matrix A is positive; but if all the eigenvalues are negative the vector of zeroes is an attractor whose basin of attraction is the entire phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Equations or systems that are nonlinear can give rise to a richer variety of behavior than can linear systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] One example is Newton's method of iterating to a root of a nonlinear expression.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] If the expression has more than one real root, some starting points for the iterative algorithm will lead to one of the roots asymptotically, and other starting points will lead to another.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The basins of attraction for the expression's roots are generally not simple—it is not simply that the points nearest one root all map there, giving a basin of attraction consisting of nearby points.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The basins of attraction can be infinite in number and arbitrarily small.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Newton's method can also be applied to complex functions to find their roots.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Each root has a basin of attraction in the complex plane; these basins can be mapped as in the image shown.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] As can be seen, the combined basin of attraction for a particular root can have many disconnected regions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For many complex functions, the boundaries of the basins of attraction are fractals.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] Parabolic partial differential equations may have finite-dimensional attractors.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The diffusive part of the equation damps higher frequencies and in some cases leads to a global attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] The *Ginzburg–Landau*, the *Kuramoto–Sivashinsky*, and the two-dimensional, forced Navier–Stokes equations are all known to have global attractors of finite dimension.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/attractor] For the three-dimensional, incompressible Navier–Stokes equation with periodic boundary conditions, if it has a global attractor, then this attractor will be of finite dimensions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] The name "bifurcation" was first introduced by Henri Poincaré in 1885 in the first paper in mathematics showing such a behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] A local bifurcation occurs when a parameter change causes the stability of an equilibrium (or fixed point) to change.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] In continuous systems, this corresponds to the real part of an eigenvalue of an equilibrium passing through zero.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] In discrete systems (described by maps), this corresponds to a fixed point having a Floquet multiplier with modulus equal to one.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] In both cases, the equilibrium is *non-hyperbolic* at the bifurcation point.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] The topological changes in the phase portrait of the system can be confined to arbitrarily small neighbourhoods of the bifurcating fixed points by moving the bifurcation parameter close to the bifurcation point (hence "local").
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to zero, the bifurcation is a steady-state bifurcation, but if the eigenvalue is non-zero but purely imaginary, this is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] For discrete dynamical systems, consider the system $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n},\lambda ).$ Then a local bifurcation occurs at $(x_{0},\lambda _{0})$ if the matrix ${\textrm {d}}f_{x_{0},\lambda _{0}}$ has an eigenvalue with modulus equal to one.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to one, the bifurcation is either a saddle-node (often called fold bifurcation in maps), transcritical or pitchfork bifurcation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to −1, it is a period-doubling (or flip) bifurcation, and otherwise, it is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations occur when "larger" invariant sets, such as periodic orbits, collide with equilibria.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] This causes changes in the topology of the trajectories in the phase space which cannot be confined to a small neighbourhood, as is the case with local bifurcations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] In fact, the changes in topology extend out to an arbitrarily large distance (hence "global").
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations can also involve more complicated sets such as chaotic attractors (e.g. crises).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] The codimension of a bifurcation is the number of parameters which must be varied for the bifurcation to occur.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] This corresponds to the codimension of the parameter set for which the bifurcation occurs within the full space of parameters.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Saddle-node bifurcations and Hopf bifurcations are the only generic local bifurcations which are really codimension-one (the others all having higher codimension).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] However, transcritical and pitchfork bifurcations are also often thought of as codimension-one, because the normal forms can be written with only one parameter.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] An example of a well-studied codimension-two bifurcation is the Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has been applied to connect quantum systems to the dynamics of their classical analogues in atomic systems, molecular systems, and resonant tunneling diodes.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has also been applied to the study of laser dynamics and a number of theoretical examples which are difficult to access experimentally such as the kicked top and coupled quantum wells.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] The dominant reason for the link between quantum systems and bifurcations in the classical equations of motion is that at bifurcations, the signature of classical orbits becomes large, as Martin Gutzwiller points out in his classic work on quantum chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/bifurcation-theory] Many kinds of bifurcations have been studied with regard to links between classical and quantum dynamics including saddle node bifurcations, Hopf bifurcations, umbilic bifurcations, period doubling bifurcations, reconnection bifurcations, tangent bifurcations, and cusp bifurcations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Small differences in initial conditions, such as those due to errors in measurements or due to rounding errors in numerical computation, can yield widely diverging outcomes for such dynamic systems, rendering long-term prediction of their behavior impossible in general.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This can happen even though these systems are deterministic, meaning that their future behavior follows a unique evolution and is fully determined by their initial conditions, with no random elements involved.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In other words, despite the deterministic nature of these systems, this does not make them predictable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This behavior is known as **deterministic chaos**, or simply **chaos**.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaotic behavior exists in many natural systems, including fluid flow, heartbeat irregularities, weather and climate.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] It also occurs spontaneously in some systems with artificial components, such as road traffic.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This behavior can be studied through the analysis of a chaotic mathematical model or through analytical techniques such as recurrence plots and Poincaré maps.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has applications in a variety of disciplines, including meteorology, anthropology, sociology, environmental science, computer science, engineering, economics, ecology, and pandemic crisis management.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The theory formed the basis for such fields of study as complex dynamical systems, edge of chaos theory and self-assembly processes.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos theory concerns deterministic systems which are predictable for some amount of time and then appear to become random.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Some examples of Lyapunov times are: Chaotic electrical circuits, about 1 millisecond; weather systems, a few days (but unproven); the inner solar system, 4 to 5 million years.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In chaotic systems, the uncertainty in a forecast increases exponentially with elapsed time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Hence, mathematically, doubling the forecast time more than squares the proportional uncertainty in the forecast.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This means, in practice, a meaningful prediction cannot be made over an interval of more than two or three times the Lyapunov time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] When meaningful predictions cannot be made, the system appears random.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In common usage, "chaos" means "a state of disorder".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, in chaos theory, the term is defined more precisely.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Although no universally accepted mathematical definition of chaos exists, a commonly used definition, originally formulated by Robert L.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In some cases, the last two properties above have been shown to actually imply sensitivity to initial conditions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In the discrete-time case, this is true for all continuous maps on metric spaces.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In these cases, while it is often the most practically significant property, "sensitivity to initial conditions" need not be stated in the definition.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] If attention is restricted to intervals, the second property implies the other two.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An alternative and a generally weaker definition of chaos uses only the first two properties in the above list.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The flapping wing represents a small change in the initial condition of the system, which causes a chain of events that prevents the predictability of large-scale phenomena.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Had the butterfly not flapped its wings, the trajectory of the overall system could have been vastly different.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] As suggested in Lorenz's book entitled *The Essence of Chaos*, published in 1993, "sensitive dependence can serve as an acceptable definition of chaos".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An idealized skiing model was developed to illustrate the sensitivity of time-varying paths to initial positions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A predictability horizon can be determined before the onset of SDIC (i.e., prior to significant separations of initial nearby trajectories).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A consequence of sensitivity to initial conditions is that if we start with a limited amount of information about the system (as is usually the case in practice), then beyond a certain time, the system would no longer be predictable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This is most prevalent in the case of weather, which is generally predictable only about a week ahead.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This does not mean that one cannot assert anything about events far in the future - only that some restrictions on the system are present.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, we know that the temperature of the surface of the earth will not naturally reach 100 °C (212 °F) or fall below −130 °C (−202 °F) on earth (during the current geologic era), but we cannot predict exactly which day will have the hottest temperature of the year.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In more mathematical terms, the Lyapunov exponent measures the sensitivity to initial conditions, in the form of rate of exponential divergence from the perturbed initial conditions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] where t is the time and $\lambda$ is the Lyapunov exponent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The rate of separation depends on the orientation of the initial separation vector, so a whole spectrum of Lyapunov exponents can exist.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The number of Lyapunov exponents is equal to the number of dimensions of the phase space, though it is common to just refer to the largest one.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, the maximal Lyapunov exponent (MLE) is most often used, because it determines the overall predictability of the system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A positive MLE, coupled with the solution's boundedness, is usually taken as an indication that the system is chaotic.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In addition to the above property, other properties related to sensitivity of initial conditions also exist.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] These include, for example, measure-theoretical mixing (as discussed in ergodic theory) and properties of a K-system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A chaotic system may have sequences of values for the evolving variable that exactly repeat themselves, giving periodic behavior starting from any point in that sequence.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, such periodic sequences are repelling rather than attracting, meaning that if the evolving variable is outside the sequence, however close, it will not enter the sequence and in fact, will diverge from it.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Thus for almost all initial conditions, the variable evolves chaotically with non-periodic behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Topological mixing (or the weaker condition of topological transitivity) means that the system evolves over time so that any given region or open set of its phase space eventually overlaps with any other given region.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This mathematical concept of "mixing" corresponds to the standard intuition, and the mixing of colored dyes or fluids is an example of a chaotic system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Topological mixing is often omitted from popular accounts of chaos, which equate chaos with only sensitivity to initial conditions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, sensitive dependence on initial conditions alone does not give chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, consider the simple dynamical system produced by repeatedly doubling an initial value.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This system has sensitive dependence on initial conditions everywhere, since any pair of nearby points eventually becomes widely separated.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, this example has no topological mixing, and therefore has no chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Indeed, it has extremely simple behavior: all points except 0 tend to positive or negative infinity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A map $f:X\to X$ is said to be topologically transitive if for any pair of non-empty open sets $U,V\subset X$ , there exists $k>0$ such that $f^{k}(U)\cap V\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Topological transitivity is a weaker version of topological mixing.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Intuitively, if a map is topologically transitive then given a point *x* and a region *V*, there exists a point *y* near *x* whose orbit passes through *V*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This implies that it is impossible to decompose the system into two open sets.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An important related theorem is the Birkhoff Transitivity Theorem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] It is easy to see that the existence of a dense orbit implies topological transitivity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The Birkhoff Transitivity Theorem states that if *X* is a second countable, complete metric space, then topological transitivity implies the existence of a dense set of points in *X* that have dense orbits.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For a chaotic system to have dense periodic orbits means that every point in the space is approached arbitrarily closely by periodic orbits.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The one-dimensional logistic map defined by *x* → 4 *x* (1 – *x*) is one of the simplest systems with density of periodic orbits.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] (indeed, for all the periods specified by Sharkovskii's theorem).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Sharkovskii's theorem is the basis of the Li and Yorke (1975) proof that any continuous one-dimensional system that exhibits a regular cycle of period three will also display regular cycles of every other length, as well as completely chaotic orbits.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Some dynamical systems, like the one-dimensional logistic map defined by *x* → 4 *x* (1 – *x*), are chaotic everywhere, but in many cases chaotic behavior is found only in a subset of phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The cases of most interest arise when the chaotic behavior takes place on an attractor, since then a large set of initial conditions leads to orbits that converge to this chaotic region.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An easy way to visualize a chaotic attractor is to start with a point in the basin of attraction of the attractor, and then simply plot its subsequent orbit.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Because of the topological transitivity condition, this is likely to produce a picture of the entire final attractor, and indeed both orbits shown in the figure on the right give a picture of the general shape of the Lorenz attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This attractor results from a simple three-dimensional model of the Lorenz weather system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The Lorenz attractor is perhaps one of the best-known chaotic system diagrams, probably because it is not only one of the first, but it is also one of the most complex, and as such gives rise to a very interesting pattern that, with a little imagination, looks like the wings of a butterfly.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Unlike fixed-point attractors and limit cycles, the attractors that arise from chaotic systems, known as strange attractors, have great detail and complexity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Strange attractors occur in both continuous dynamical systems (such as the Lorenz system) and in some discrete systems (such as the Hénon map).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Other discrete dynamical systems have a repelling structure called a Julia set, which forms at the boundary between basins of attraction of fixed points.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Julia sets can be thought of as strange repellers.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Both strange attractors and Julia sets typically have a fractal structure, and the fractal dimension can be calculated for them.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In contrast to single type chaotic solutions, studies using Lorenz models have emphasized the importance of considering various types of solutions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, coexisting chaotic and non-chaotic may appear within the same model (e.g., the double pendulum system) using the same modeling configurations but different initial conditions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The findings of attractor coexistence, obtained from classical and generalized Lorenz models, suggested a revised view that "the entirety of weather possesses a dual nature of chaos and order with distinct predictability", in contrast to the conventional view of "weather is chaotic".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Discrete chaotic systems, such as the logistic map, can exhibit strange attractors whatever their dimensionality.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In contrast, for continuous dynamical systems, the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem shows that a strange attractor can only arise in three or more dimensions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Finite-dimensional linear systems are never chaotic; for a dynamical system to display chaotic behavior, it must be either nonlinear or infinite-dimensional.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The Poincaré–Bendixson theorem states that a two-dimensional differential equation has very regular behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] where x , y , and z make up the system state, t is time, and $\sigma$ , $\rho$ , $\beta$ are the system parameters.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Five of the terms on the right hand side are linear, while two are quadratic; a total of seven terms.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Another well-known chaotic attractor is generated by the Rössler equations, which have only one nonlinear term out of seven.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Sprott found a three-dimensional system with just five terms, that had only one nonlinear term, which exhibits chaos for certain parameter values.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Zhang and Heidel showed that, at least for dissipative and conservative quadratic systems, three-dimensional quadratic systems with only three or four terms on the right-hand side cannot exhibit chaotic behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The reason is, simply put, that solutions to such systems are asymptotic to a two-dimensional surface and therefore solutions are well behaved.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] While the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem shows that a continuous dynamical system on the Euclidean plane cannot be chaotic, two-dimensional continuous systems with non-Euclidean geometry can still exhibit some chaotic properties.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The above set of three ordinary differential equations has been referred to as the three-dimensional Lorenz model.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Since 1963, higher-dimensional Lorenz models have been developed in numerous studies for examining the impact of an increased degree of nonlinearity, as well as its collective effect with heating and dissipations, on solution stability.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Perhaps surprisingly, chaos may occur also in linear systems, provided they are infinite dimensional.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A theory of linear chaos is being developed in functional analysis.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] $f[\psi _{n}({\vec {r}},t)]$ might be logistic map alike $\psi \rightarrow G\psi [1-\tanh(\psi )]$ or complex map.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] When wave propagation problems at distance $L=ct$ with wavelength $\lambda =2\pi /k$ are considered the kernel K may have a form of Green function for Schrödinger equation:.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Under the right conditions, chaos spontaneously evolves into a lockstep pattern.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In the Kuramoto model, four conditions suffice to produce synchronization in a chaotic system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Examples include the coupled oscillation of Christiaan Huygens' pendulums, fireflies, neurons, the London Millennium Bridge resonance, and large arrays of Josephson junctions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Moreover, from the theoretical physics standpoint, dynamical chaos itself, in its most general manifestation, is a spontaneous order.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The essence here is that most orders in nature arise from the spontaneous breakdown of various symmetries.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This large family of phenomena includes elasticity, superconductivity, ferromagnetism, and many others.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] According to the supersymmetric theory of stochastic dynamics, chaos, or more precisely, its stochastic generalization, is also part of this family.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The corresponding symmetry being broken is the topological supersymmetry which is hidden in all stochastic (partial) differential equations, and the corresponding order parameter is a field-theoretic embodiment of the butterfly effect.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] There are also definitions of chaos that don't require the sensitivity on initial conditions property, such as combinatorial chaos (I.e. applying recursively a discrete combinatorial action).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This is also comparable and similar to chaos generated by cellular automata.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This is important because, as this type of chaos can be equivalent to a turing machine, it is possible to execute computation with such dynamical systems, which is an intuitive way to see that the halting problem is not decidable, implying that some computational algorithms may never end.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Unpredictability in this type of system is typically of a different nature than that of other types of chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] James Clerk Maxwell was the first scientist to emphasize the importance of initial conditions, and he is seen as being one of the earliest to discuss chaos theory, with work in the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In the 1880s, while studying the three-body problem, Henri Poincaré found that there can be orbits that are nonperiodic, and yet not forever increasing nor approaching a fixed point.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1898, Jacques Hadamard published an influential study of the motion of a free particle gliding frictionlessly on a surface of constant negative curvature, called "Hadamard's billiards".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Hadamard was able to show that all trajectories are unstable, in that all particle trajectories diverge exponentially from one another, with a positive Lyapunov exponent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Later studies, also on the topic of nonlinear differential equations, were carried out by George David Birkhoff, Andrey Nikolaevich Kolmogorov, Mary Lucy Cartwright and John Edensor Littlewood, and Stephen Smale.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Experimentalists and mathematicians had encountered turbulence in fluid motion, chaotic behaviour in society and economy, nonperiodic oscillation in radio circuits and fractal patterns in nature without the benefit of a theory to explain what they were seeing.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Both of these observations underline the connection of chaos to either stochastic or non-linear dynamical systems, but definitely non-differentiable and non-continuous time evolution.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] What had been attributed to measure imprecision and simple "noise" was considered by chaos theorists as a full component of the studied systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1959 Boris Valerianovich Chirikov proposed a criterion for the emergence of classical chaos in Hamiltonian systems (Chirikov criterion).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] He applied this criterion to explain some experimental results on plasma confinement in open mirror traps.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This is regarded as the very first physical theory of chaos, which succeeded in explaining a concrete experiment.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] And Boris Chirikov himself is considered as a pioneer in classical and quantum chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The main catalyst for the development of chaos theory was the electronic computer.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Much of the mathematics of chaos theory involves the repeated iteration of simple mathematical formulas, which would be impractical to do by hand.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Electronic computers made these repeated calculations practical, while figures and images made it possible to visualize these systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] As a graduate student in Chihiro Hayashi's laboratory at Kyoto University, Yoshisuke Ueda was experimenting with analog computers and noticed, on November 27, 1961, what he called "randomly transitional phenomena".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Yet his advisor did not agree with his conclusions at the time, and did not allow him to report his findings until 1970.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Edward Lorenz was an early pioneer of the theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] His interest in chaos came about accidentally through his work on weather prediction in 1961.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Lorenz and his collaborator Ellen Fetter and Margaret Hamilton were using a simple digital computer, a Royal McBee LGP-30, to run weather simulations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] They wanted to see a sequence of data again, and to save time they started the simulation in the middle of its course.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] They did this by entering a printout of the data that corresponded to conditions in the middle of the original simulation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] To their surprise, the weather the machine began to predict was completely different from the previous calculation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] They tracked this down to the computer printout.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The computer worked with 6-digit precision, but the printout rounded variables off to a 3-digit number, so a value like 0.506127 printed as 0.506.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This difference is tiny, and the consensus at the time would have been that it should have no practical effect.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, Lorenz discovered that small changes in initial conditions produced large changes in long-term outcome.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Lorenz's discovery, which gave its name to Lorenz attractors, showed that even detailed atmospheric modeling cannot, in general, make precise long-term weather predictions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1963, Benoit Mandelbrot, studying information theory, discovered that noise in many phenomena (including stock prices and telephone circuits) was patterned like a Cantor set, a set of points with infinite roughness and detail.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Mandelbrot described both the "Noah effect" (in which sudden discontinuous changes can occur) and the "Joseph effect" (in which persistence of a value can occur for a while, yet suddenly change afterwards).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1967, he published "How long is the coast of Britain?
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Statistical self-similarity and fractional dimension", showing that a coastline's length varies with the scale of the measuring instrument, resembles itself at all scales, and is infinite in length for an infinitesimally small measuring device.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Arguing that a ball of twine appears as a point when viewed from far away (0-dimensional), a ball when viewed from fairly near (3-dimensional), or a curved strand (1-dimensional), he argued that the dimensions of an object are relative to the observer and may be fractional.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An object whose irregularity is constant over different scales ("self-similarity") is a fractal (examples include the Menger sponge, the Sierpiński gasket, and the Koch curve or *snowflake*, which is infinitely long yet encloses a finite space and has a fractal dimension of circa 1.2619).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1982, Mandelbrot published *The Fractal Geometry of Nature*, which became a classic of chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In December 1977, the New York Academy of Sciences organized the first symposium on chaos, attended by David Ruelle, Robert May, James A.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Yorke (coiner of the term "chaos" as used in mathematics), Robert Shaw, and the meteorologist Edward Lorenz.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The following year Pierre Coullet and Charles Tresser published "Itérations d'endomorphismes et groupe de renormalisation", and Mitchell Feigenbaum's article "Quantitative Universality for a Class of Nonlinear Transformations" finally appeared in a journal, after 3 years of referee rejections.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Thus Feigenbaum (1975) and Coullet & Tresser (1978) discovered the universality in chaos, permitting the application of chaos theory to many different phenomena.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Libchaber, during a symposium organized in Aspen by Pierre Hohenberg, presented his experimental observation of the bifurcation cascade that leads to chaos and turbulence in Rayleigh–Bénard convection systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] He was awarded the Wolf Prize in Physics in 1986 along with Mitchell J.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Feigenbaum for their inspiring achievements.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1986, the New York Academy of Sciences co-organized with the National Institute of Mental Health and the Office of Naval Research the first important conference on chaos in biology and medicine.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] There, Bernardo Huberman presented a mathematical model of the eye tracking dysfunction among people with schizophrenia.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This led to a renewal of physiology in the 1980s through the application of chaos theory, for example, in the study of pathological cardiac cycles.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In 1987, Per Bak, Chao Tang and Kurt Wiesenfeld published a paper in *Physical Review Letters* describing for the first time self-organized criticality (SOC), considered one of the mechanisms by which complexity arises in nature.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Alongside largely lab-based approaches such as the Bak–Tang–Wiesenfeld sandpile, many other investigations have focused on large-scale natural or social systems that are known (or suspected) to display scale-invariant behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Given the implications of a scale-free distribution of event sizes, some researchers have suggested that another phenomenon that should be considered an example of SOC is the occurrence of wars.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] These investigations of SOC have included both attempts at modelling (either developing new models or adapting existing ones to the specifics of a given natural system), and extensive data analysis to determine the existence and/or characteristics of natural scaling laws.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Also in 1987 James Gleick published *Chaos: Making a New Science*, which became a best-seller and introduced the general principles of chaos theory as well as its history to the broad public.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Initially the domain of a few, isolated individuals, chaos theory progressively emerged as a transdisciplinary and institutional discipline, mainly under the name of nonlinear systems analysis.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Alluding to Thomas Kuhn's concept of a paradigm shift exposed in *The Structure of Scientific Revolutions* (1962), many "chaologists" (as some described themselves) claimed that this new theory was an example of such a shift, a thesis upheld by Gleick.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The availability of cheaper, more powerful computers broadens the applicability of chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Currently, chaos theory remains an active area of research, involving many different disciplines such as mathematics, topology, physics, social systems, population modeling, biology, meteorology, astrophysics, information theory, computational neuroscience, pandemic crisis management, etc.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For want of a horse, the rider was lost.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For want of a rider, the battle was lost.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For want of a battle, the kingdom was lost.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] And all for the want of a horseshoe nail.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Based on the above, many people mistakenly believe that the impact of a tiny initial perturbation monotonically increases with time and that any tiny perturbation can eventually produce a large impact on numerical integrations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] However, in 2008, Lorenz stated that he did not feel that this verse described true chaos but that it better illustrated the simpler phenomenon of instability and that the verse implicitly suggests that subsequent small events will not reverse the outcome.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Based on the analysis, the verse only indicates divergence, not boundedness.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Boundedness is important for the finite size of a butterfly pattern.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The characteristic of the aforementioned verse was described as "finite-time sensitive dependence".
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Although chaos theory was born from observing weather patterns, it has become applicable to a variety of other situations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Some areas benefiting from chaos theory today are geology, mathematics, biology, computer science, economics, engineering, finance, meteorology, philosophy, anthropology, physics, politics, population dynamics, and robotics.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] A few categories are listed below with examples, but this is by no means a comprehensive list as new applications are appearing.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has been used for many years in cryptography.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In the past few decades, chaos and nonlinear dynamics have been used in the design of hundreds of cryptographic primitives.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] These algorithms include image encryption algorithms, hash functions, secure pseudo-random number generators, stream ciphers, watermarking, and steganography.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The majority of these algorithms are based on uni-modal chaotic maps and a big portion of these algorithms use the control parameters and the initial condition of the chaotic maps as their keys.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] From a wider perspective, without loss of generality, the similarities between the chaotic maps and the cryptographic systems is the main motivation for the design of chaos based cryptographic algorithms.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] One type of encryption, secret key or symmetric key, relies on diffusion and confusion, which is modeled well by chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Another type of computing, DNA computing, when paired with chaos theory, offers a way to encrypt images and other information.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Many of the DNA-Chaos cryptographic algorithms are proven to be either not secure, or the technique applied is suggested to be not efficient.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Robotics is another area that has recently benefited from chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Instead of robots acting in a trial-and-error type of refinement to interact with their environment, chaos theory has been used to build a predictive model.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaotic dynamics have been exhibited by passive walking biped robots.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For over a hundred years, biologists have been keeping track of populations of different species with population models.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Most models are continuous, but recently scientists have been able to implement chaotic models in certain populations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, a study on models of Canadian lynx showed there was chaotic behavior in the population growth.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos can also be found in ecological systems, such as hydrology.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] While a chaotic model for hydrology has its shortcomings, there is still much to learn from looking at the data through the lens of chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Another biological application is found in cardiotocography.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Fetal surveillance is a delicate balance of obtaining accurate information while being as noninvasive as possible.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Better models of warning signs of fetal hypoxia can be obtained through chaotic modeling.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] As Perry points out, modeling of chaotic time series in ecology is helped by constraint.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] There is always potential difficulty in distinguishing real chaos from chaos that is only in the model.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Hence both constraint in the model and or duplicate time series data for comparison will be helpful in constraining the model to something close to the reality, for example Perry & Wall 1984.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Gene-for-gene co-evolution sometimes shows chaotic dynamics in allele frequencies.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Adding variables exaggerates this: Chaos is more common in models incorporating additional variables to reflect additional facets of real populations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] May himself did some of these foundational crop co-evolution studies, and this in turn helped shape the entire field.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Even for a steady environment, merely combining one crop and one pathogen may result in quasi-periodic- or chaotic- oscillations in pathogen population.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] It is possible that economic models can also be improved through an application of chaos theory, but predicting the health of an economic system and what factors influence it most is an extremely complex task.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The empirical literature that tests for chaos in economics and finance presents very mixed results, in part due to confusion between specific tests for chaos and more general tests for non-linear relationships.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos could be found in economics by the means of recurrence quantification analysis.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In fact, Orlando et al. by the means of the so-called recurrence quantification correlation index were able to detect hidden changes in time series.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Then, the same technique was employed to detect transitions from laminar (regular) to turbulent (chaotic) phases as well as differences between macroeconomic variables and highlight hidden features of economic dynamics.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Finally, chaos theory could help in modeling how an economy operates as well as in embedding shocks due to external events such as COVID-19.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Due to the sensitive dependence of solutions on initial conditions (SDIC), also known as the butterfly effect, chaotic systems like the Lorenz 1963 model imply a finite predictability horizon.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This means that while accurate predictions are possible over a finite time period, they are not feasible over an infinite time span.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Considering the nature of Lorenz's chaotic solutions, the committee led by Charney et al. in 1966 extrapolated a doubling time of five days from a general circulation model, suggesting a predictability limit of two weeks.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] This connection between the five-day doubling time and the two-week predictability limit was also recorded in a 1969 report by the Global Atmospheric Research Program (GARP).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] To acknowledge the combined direct and indirect influences from the Mintz and Arakawa model and Lorenz's models, as well as the leadership of Charney et al., Shen et al. refer to the two-week predictability limit as the "Predictability Limit Hypothesis," drawing an analogy to Moore's Law.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In AI-driven large language models, responses can exhibit sensitivities to factors like alterations in formatting and variations in prompts.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] These sensitivities are akin to butterfly effects.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In chemistry, predicting gas solubility is essential to manufacturing polymers, but models using particle swarm optimization (PSO) tend to converge to the wrong points.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] An improved version of PSO has been created by introducing chaos, which keeps the simulations from getting stuck.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In celestial mechanics, especially when observing asteroids, applying chaos theory leads to better predictions about when these objects will approach Earth and other planets.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Four of the five moons of Pluto rotate chaotically.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In quantum physics and electrical engineering, the study of large arrays of Josephson junctions benefitted greatly from chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Closer to home, coal mines have always been dangerous places where frequent natural gas leaks cause many deaths.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Until recently, there was no reliable way to predict when they would occur.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] But these gas leaks have chaotic tendencies that, when properly modeled, can be predicted fairly accurately.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Glass and Mandell and Selz have found that no EEG study has as yet indicated the presence of strange attractors or other signs of chaotic behavior.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Redington and Reidbord (1992) attempted to demonstrate that the human heart could display chaotic traits.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] They monitored the changes in between-heartbeat intervals for a single psychotherapy patient as she moved through periods of varying emotional intensity during a therapy session.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] In their 1995 paper, Metcalf and Allen maintained that they uncovered in animal behavior a pattern of period doubling leading to chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The authors examined a well-known response called schedule-induced polydipsia, by which an animal deprived of food for certain lengths of time will drink unusual amounts of water when the food is at last presented.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The control parameter (r) operating here was the length of the interval between feedings, once resumed.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The authors were careful to test a large number of animals and to include many replications, and they designed their experiment so as to rule out the likelihood that changes in response patterns were caused by different starting places for r.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Time series and first delay plots provide the best support for the claims made, showing a fairly clear march from periodicity to irregularity as the feeding times were increased.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] The various phase trajectory plots and spectral analyses, on the other hand, do not match up well enough with the other graphs or with the overall theory to lead inexorably to a chaotic diagnosis.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For example, the phase trajectories do not show a definite progression towards greater and greater complexity (and away from periodicity); the process seems quite muddied.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Also, where Metcalf and Allen saw periods of two and six in their spectral plots, there is room for alternative interpretations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] All of this ambiguity necessitate some serpentine, post-hoc explanation to show that results fit a chaotic model.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] By adapting a model of career counseling to include a chaotic interpretation of the relationship between employees and the job market, Amundson and Bright found that better suggestions can be made to people struggling with career decisions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Modern organizations are increasingly seen as open complex adaptive systems with fundamental natural nonlinear structures, subject to internal and external forces that may contribute chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] For instance, team building and group development is increasingly being researched as an inherently unpredictable system, as the uncertainty of different individuals meeting for the first time makes the trajectory of the team unknowable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Traffic forecasting may benefit from applications of chaos theory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Better predictions of when a congestion will occur would allow measures to be taken to disperse it before it would have occurred.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Combining chaos theory principles with a few other methods has led to a more accurate short-term prediction model, such as the BML traffic model.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Chaos theory has been applied to environmental water cycle data (also hydrological data), such as rainfall and streamflow.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] These studies have yielded controversial results, because the methods for detecting a chaotic signature are often relatively subjective.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/chaos-theory] Early studies tended to "succeed" in finding chaos, whereas subsequent studies and meta-analyses called those studies into question and provided explanations for why these datasets are not likely to have low-dimension chaotic dynamics.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] In mathematics, in the study of dynamical systems with two-dimensional phase space, a **limit cycle** is a closed trajectory in phase space having the property that at least one other trajectory spirals into it either as time approaches infinity or as time approaches negative infinity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Such behavior is exhibited in some nonlinear systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Limit cycles have been used to model the behavior of many real-world oscillatory systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] The study of limit cycles was initiated by Henri Poincaré (1854–1912).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] We consider a two-dimensional dynamical system of the form $x'(t)=V(x(t))$ where $V:\mathbb {R} ^{2}\to \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is a smooth function.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] A *trajectory* of this system is some smooth function $x(t)$ with values in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ which satisfies this differential equation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Such a trajectory is called *closed* (or *periodic*) if it is not constant but returns to its starting point, i.e. if there exists some $t_{0}>0$ such that $x(t+t_{0})=x(t)$ for all $t\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] An orbit is the image of a trajectory, a subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] A *closed orbit*, or *cycle*, is the image of a closed trajectory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] A *limit cycle* is a cycle which is the limit set of some other trajectory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] By the Jordan curve theorem, every closed trajectory divides the plane into two regions, the interior and the exterior of the curve.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] The corresponding statement holds for a trajectory in the interior that approaches the limit cycle for time approaching $-\infty$ , and also for trajectories in the exterior approaching the limit cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] In the case where all the neighboring trajectories approach the limit cycle as time approaches infinity, it is called a *stable* or *attractive* limit cycle (ω-limit cycle).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] If instead, all neighboring trajectories approach it as time approaches negative infinity, then it is an *unstable* limit cycle (α-limit cycle).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] If there is a neighboring trajectory which spirals into the limit cycle as time approaches infinity, and another one which spirals into it as time approaches negative infinity, then it is a *semi-stable* limit cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] There are also limit cycles that are neither stable, unstable nor semi-stable: for instance, a neighboring trajectory may approach the limit cycle from the outside, but the inside of the limit cycle is approached by a family of other cycles (which would not be limit cycles).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Stable limit cycles are examples of attractors.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] They imply self-sustained oscillations: the closed trajectory describes the perfect periodic behavior of the system, and any small perturbation from this closed trajectory causes the system to return to it, making the system stick to the limit cycle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Every closed trajectory contains within its interior a stationary point of the system, i.e. a point p where $V'(p)=0$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] The Bendixson–Dulac theorem and the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem predict the absence or existence, respectively, of limit cycles of two-dimensional nonlinear dynamical systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Finding limit cycles, in general, is a very difficult problem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] The number of limit cycles of a polynomial differential equation in the plane is the main object of the second part of Hilbert's sixteenth problem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] It is unknown, for instance, whether there is any system $x'=V(x)$ in the plane where both components of V are quadratic polynomials of the two variables, such that the system has more than 4 limit cycles.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/limit-cycle] Limit cycles are important in many scientific applications where systems with self-sustained oscillations are modelled.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] In mathematics, the **Lyapunov exponent** or **Lyapunov characteristic exponent** of a dynamical system is a quantity that characterizes the exponential rate of separation of infinitesimally close trajectories.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] where $\lambda$ is the Lyapunov exponent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The rate of separation can be different for different orientations of initial separation vector.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Thus, there is a **spectrum of Lyapunov exponents**—equal in number to the dimensionality of the phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] It is common to refer to the largest one as the **maximal Lyapunov exponent** (MLE), because it determines a notion of predictability for a dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] A positive MLE is usually taken as an indication that the system is chaotic (provided some other conditions are met, e.g., phase space compactness).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] This is because for the MLE to be more than 0, the average derivative needs to be more than 1, since we find its logarithms.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] If the average derivatives are above 1, it means that the function grows exponentially, which makes it so that any small change between initial values increase from their original value, so the function is divergent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] If it is less than 0, it means that the average derivative is less than 1, which means that the function is decreasing, which would make any changes in the initial values decrease over time, making the function convergent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Note that an arbitrary initial separation vector will typically contain some component in the direction associated with the MLE, and because of the exponential growth rate, the effect of the other exponents will diminish over time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The exponent is named after Aleksandr Lyapunov.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The limit $|{\boldsymbol {\delta }}_{0}|\to 0$ ensures the validity of the linear approximation at any time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] For a dynamical system with evolution equation ${\dot {x}}_{i}=f_{i}(x)$ in an *n*–dimensional phase space, the spectrum of Lyapunov exponents $\{\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},\ldots ,\lambda _{n}\}\,,$ in general, depends on the starting point $x_{0}$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] However, we will usually be interested in the attractor (or attractors) of a dynamical system, and there will normally be one set of exponents associated with each attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The choice of starting point may determine which attractor the system ends up on, if there is more than one.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The matrix Y describes how a small change at the point $x(0)$ propagates to the final point $x(t)$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The limit $\Lambda =\lim _{t\rightarrow \infty }{\frac {1}{2t}}\log(Y(t)Y^{T}(t))$ defines a matrix $\Lambda$ (the conditions for the existence of the limit are given by the Oseledets theorem).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov exponents $\lambda _{i}$ are defined by the eigenvalues of $\Lambda$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The set of Lyapunov exponents will be the same for almost all starting points of an ergodic component of the dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The singular values $\{\alpha _{j}{\big (}X(t){\big )}\}_{1}^{n}$ of the matrix $X(t)$ are the square roots of the eigenvalues of the matrix $X(t)^{*}X(t)$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Perron that the requirement of regularity of the first approximation is substantial.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Perron constructed an example of a second-order system, where the first approximation has negative Lyapunov exponents along a zero solution of the original system but, at the same time, this zero solution of the original nonlinear system is Lyapunov unstable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Furthermore, in a certain neighborhood of this zero solution almost all solutions of the original system have positive Lyapunov exponents.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Also, it is possible to construct a reverse example in which the first approximation has positive Lyapunov exponents along a zero solution of the original system but, at the same time, this zero solution of original nonlinear system is Lyapunov stable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The effect of sign inversion of Lyapunov exponents of solutions of the original system and the system of first approximation with the same initial data was subsequently called the Perron effect.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Perron's counterexample shows that a negative largest Lyapunov exponent does not, in general, indicate stability, and that a positive largest Lyapunov exponent does not, in general, indicate chaos.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Therefore, time-varying linearization requires additional justification.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is conservative (i.e., there is no dissipation), a volume element of the phase space will stay the same along a trajectory.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Thus the sum of all Lyapunov exponents must be zero.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is dissipative, the sum of Lyapunov exponents is negative.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] If the system is a flow and the trajectory does not converge to a single point, one exponent is always zero—the Lyapunov exponent corresponding to the eigenvalue of L with an eigenvector in the direction of the flow.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov spectrum can be used to give an estimate of the rate of entropy production, of the fractal dimension, and of the Hausdorff dimension of the considered dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Moreover, the sum of all the positive Lyapunov exponents gives an estimate of the Kolmogorov–Sinai entropy accordingly to Pesin's theorem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Along with widely used numerical methods for estimating and computing the Lyapunov dimension there is an effective analytical approach, which is based on the direct Lyapunov method with special Lyapunov-like functions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov exponents of bounded trajectory and the Lyapunov dimension of attractor are invariant under diffeomorphism of the phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The multiplicative inverse of the largest Lyapunov exponent is sometimes referred in literature as Lyapunov time, and defines the characteristic *e*-folding time.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] For chaotic orbits, the Lyapunov time will be finite, whereas for regular orbits it will be infinite.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Generally the calculation of Lyapunov exponents, as defined above, cannot be carried out analytically, and in most cases one must resort to numerical techniques.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] An early example, which also constituted the first demonstration of the exponential divergence of chaotic trajectories, was carried out by R.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Currently, the most commonly used numerical procedure estimates the L matrix based on averaging several finite time approximations of the limit defining L .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] One of the most used and effective numerical techniques to calculate the Lyapunov spectrum for a smooth dynamical system relies on periodic Gram–Schmidt orthonormalization of the Lyapunov vectors to avoid a misalignment of all the vectors along the direction of maximal expansion.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The Lyapunov spectrum of various models are described.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Source code is provided for several nonlinear systems, including the Hénon map, the Lorenz system, and a delay differential equation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Calculating Lyapunov exponents from limited experimental data presents significant challenges.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The primary difficulty arises because such data is typically confined to the system's attractor and does not explore the full phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] This confinement results in a 'singular' dataset with minimal extension along certain directions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] These singular directions are precisely those associated with the more negative Lyapunov exponents, making them notoriously difficult to determine accurately.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] To address this, one effective technique is to use nonlinear mappings to model the evolution of small displacements from the attractor.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] This approach can dramatically improve the ability to recover the full Lyapunov spectrum, but it is highly sensitive to noise and requires very clean data to be effective.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Whereas the (global) Lyapunov exponent gives a measure for the total predictability of a system, it is sometimes of interest to estimate the local predictability around a point *x*0 in phase space.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] This may be done through the eigenvalues of the Jacobian matrix *J*0(*x*0).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] These eigenvalues are also called local Lyapunov exponents.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Local exponents are not invariant under a nonlinear change of coordinates.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] This term is normally used regarding synchronization of chaos, in which there are two systems that are coupled, usually in a unidirectional manner so that there is a drive (or master) system and a response (or slave) system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] The conditional exponents are those of the response system with the drive system treated as simply the source of a (chaotic) drive signal.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/lyapunov-exponent] Synchronization occurs when all of the conditional exponents are negative.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] In mathematics and science, a **nonlinear system** (or a **non-linear system**) is a system in which the change of the output is not proportional to the change of the input.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear problems are of interest to engineers, biologists, physicists, mathematicians, and many other scientists since most systems are inherently nonlinear in nature.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear dynamical systems, describing changes in variables over time, may appear chaotic, unpredictable, or counterintuitive, contrasting with much simpler linear systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] In other words, in a nonlinear system of equations, the equation(s) to be solved cannot be written as a linear combination of the unknown variables or functions that appear in them.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Systems can be defined as nonlinear, regardless of whether known linear functions appear in the equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] In particular, a differential equation is *linear* if it is linear in terms of the unknown function and its derivatives, even if nonlinear in terms of the other variables appearing in it.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] As nonlinear dynamical equations are difficult to solve, nonlinear systems are commonly approximated by linear equations (linearization).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This works well up to some accuracy and some range for the input values, but some interesting phenomena such as solitons, chaos, and singularities are hidden by linearization.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] It follows that some aspects of the dynamic behavior of a nonlinear system can appear to be counterintuitive, unpredictable or even chaotic.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Although such chaotic behavior may resemble random behavior, it is in fact not random.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] For example, some aspects of the weather are seen to be chaotic, where simple changes in one part of the system produce complex effects throughout.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This nonlinearity is one of the reasons why accurate long-term forecasts are impossible with current technology.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Some authors use the term **nonlinear science** for the study of nonlinear systems.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Additivity implies homogeneity for any rational *α*, and, for continuous functions, for any real *α*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] For a complex *α*, homogeneity does not follow from additivity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] For example, an antilinear map is additive but not homogeneous.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] is called **linear** if $f(x)$ is a linear map (as defined above) and **nonlinear** otherwise.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] The equation is called *homogeneous* if $C=0$ and $f(x)$ is a homogeneous function.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] The definition $f(x)=C$ is very general in that x can be any sensible mathematical object (number, vector, function, etc.), and the function $f(x)$ can literally be any mapping, including integration or differentiation with associated constraints (such as boundary values).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] If $f(x)$ contains differentiation with respect to x , the result will be a differential equation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear system of equations consists of a set of equations in several variables such that at least one of them is not a linear equation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] For a single equation of the form $f(x)=0,$ many methods have been designed; see Root-finding algorithm.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] In the case where f is a polynomial, one has a *polynomial equation* such as $x^{2}+x-1=0.$ The general root-finding algorithms apply to polynomial roots, but, generally they do not find all the roots, and when they fail to find a root, this does not imply that there is no roots.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Specific methods for polynomials allow finding all roots or the real roots; see real-root isolation.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Solving systems of polynomial equations, that is finding the common zeros of a set of several polynomials in several variables is a difficult problem for which elaborate algorithms have been designed, such as Gröbner base algorithms.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] For the general case of system of equations formed by equating to zero several differentiable functions, the main method is Newton's method and its variants.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Generally they may provide a solution, but do not provide any information on the number of solutions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear recurrence relation defines successive terms of a sequence as a nonlinear function of preceding terms.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear recurrence relations are the logistic map and the relations that define the various Hofstadter sequences.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear discrete models that represent a wide class of nonlinear recurrence relationships include the NARMAX (Nonlinear Autoregressive Moving Average with eXogenous inputs) model and the related nonlinear system identification and analysis procedures.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] These approaches can be used to study a wide class of complex nonlinear behaviors in the time, frequency, and spatio-temporal domains.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A system of differential equations is said to be nonlinear if it is not a system of linear equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Problems involving nonlinear differential equations are extremely diverse, and methods of solution or analysis are problem dependent.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear differential equations are the Navier–Stokes equations in fluid dynamics and the Lotka–Volterra equations in biology.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] One of the greatest difficulties of nonlinear problems is that it is not generally possible to combine known solutions into new solutions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] In linear problems, for example, a family of linearly independent solutions can be used to construct general solutions through the superposition principle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A good example of this is one-dimensional heat transport with Dirichlet boundary conditions, the solution of which can be written as a time-dependent linear combination of sinusoids of differing frequencies; this makes solutions very flexible.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] It is often possible to find several very specific solutions to nonlinear equations, however the lack of a superposition principle prevents the construction of new solutions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] First order ordinary differential equations are often exactly solvable by separation of variables, especially for autonomous equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] has $u={\frac {1}{x+C}}$ as a general solution (and also the special solution $u=0,$ corresponding to the limit of the general solution when *C* tends to infinity).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] and the left-hand side of the equation is not a linear function of u and its derivatives.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Note that if the $u^{2}$ term were replaced with u , the problem would be linear (the exponential decay problem).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Second and higher order ordinary differential equations (more generally, systems of nonlinear equations) rarely yield closed-form solutions, though implicit solutions and solutions involving nonelementary integrals are encountered.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] The most common basic approach to studying nonlinear partial differential equations is to change the variables (or otherwise transform the problem) so that the resulting problem is simpler (possibly linear).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Sometimes, the equation may be transformed into one or more ordinary differential equations, as seen in separation of variables, which is always useful whether or not the resulting ordinary differential equation(s) is solvable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Another common (though less mathematical) tactic, often exploited in fluid and heat mechanics, is to use scale analysis to simplify a general, natural equation in a certain specific boundary value problem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Other methods include examining the characteristics and using the methods outlined above for ordinary differential equations.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A classic, extensively studied nonlinear problem is the dynamics of a frictionless pendulum under the influence of gravity.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] where gravity points "downwards" and $\theta$ is the angle the pendulum forms with its rest position, as shown in the figure at right.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] which is an implicit solution involving an elliptic integral.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This "solution" generally does not have many uses because most of the nature of the solution is hidden in the nonelementary integral (nonelementary unless $C_{0}=2$ ).
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Another way to approach the problem is to linearize any nonlinearity (the sine function term in this case) at the various points of interest through Taylor expansions.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \theta$ for $\theta \approx 0$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This is a simple harmonic oscillator corresponding to oscillations of the pendulum near the bottom of its path.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \pi -\theta$ for $\theta \approx \pi$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] The solution to this problem involves hyperbolic sinusoids, and note that unlike the small angle approximation, this approximation is unstable, meaning that $|\theta |$ will usually grow without limit, though bounded solutions are possible.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to the difficulty of balancing a pendulum upright, it is literally an unstable state.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to a free fall problem.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] A very useful qualitative picture of the pendulum's dynamics may be obtained by piecing together such linearizations, as seen in the figure at right.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/nonlinear-system] Other techniques may be used to find (exact) phase portraits and approximate periods.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] More precisely, one considers a periodic orbit with initial conditions within a section of the space, which leaves that section afterwards, and observes the point at which this orbit first returns to the section.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] One then creates a map to send the first point to the second, hence the name *first recurrence map*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] The transversality of the Poincaré section means that periodic orbits starting on the subspace flow through it and not parallel to it.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] A Poincaré map can be interpreted as a discrete dynamical system with a state space that is one dimension smaller than the original continuous dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Because it preserves many properties of periodic and quasiperiodic orbits of the original system and has a lower-dimensional state space, it is often used for analyzing the original system in a simpler way.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] In practice this is not always possible as there is no general method to construct a Poincaré map.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] A Poincaré map differs from a recurrence plot in that space, not time, determines when to plot a point.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] For instance, the locus of the Moon when the Earth is at perihelion is a recurrence plot; the locus of the Moon when it passes through the plane perpendicular to the Earth's orbit and passing through the Sun and the Earth at perihelion is a Poincaré map.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] It was used by Michel Hénon to study the motion of stars in a galaxy, because the path of a star projected onto a plane looks like a tangled mess, while the Poincaré map shows the structure more clearly.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Let (**R**, *M*, *φ*) be a global dynamical system, with **R** the real numbers, *M* the phase space and *φ* the evolution function.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Let γ be a periodic orbit through a point *p* and *S* be a local differentiable and transversal section of *φ* through *p*, called a **Poincaré section** through *p*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Therefore, the solution with initial data $(\theta _{0},r_{0}\neq 1)$ draws a spiral that tends towards the radius 1 circle.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] We can take as Poincaré section for this flow the positive horizontal axis, namely $\Sigma =\{(\theta ,r)\ :\ \theta =0\}$ : obviously we can use r as coordinate on the section.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Every point in $\Sigma$ returns to the section after a time $t=2\pi$ (this can be understood by looking at the evolution of the angle): we can take as Poincaré map the restriction of $\Phi$ to the section $\Sigma$ computed at the time $2\pi$ , $\Phi _{2\pi }|_{\Sigma }$ .
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Poincaré maps can be interpreted as a discrete dynamical system.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] The stability of a periodic orbit of the original system is closely related to the stability of the fixed point of the corresponding Poincaré map.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Let (**R**, *M*, *φ*) be a differentiable dynamical system with periodic orbit γ through *p*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] be the corresponding Poincaré map through *p*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] Per definition this system has a fixed point at *p*.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] The periodic orbit γ of the continuous dynamical system is stable if and only if the fixed point *p* of the discrete dynamical system is stable.
[src:nonlinear-dynamics-physics/poincaré-map] The periodic orbit γ of the continuous dynamical system is asymptotically stable if and only if the fixed point *p* of the discrete dynamical system is asymptotically stable.
